data.content:
Replace `[ExpectedException]` with `Assert.ThrowsException<T>`, which pinpoints the exact throwing line and avoids false positives:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void CreateUser_NullEmail_ThrowsException()
{
    var service = new UserService();

    Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentNullException>(
        () => service.CreateUser(null, "John"));
}
```

**Why:** `[ExpectedException]` passes if *any* line throws, masking bugs (e.g., the constructor could throw instead of `CreateUser`). `Assert.ThrowsException` scopes the assertion to the exact call.

If you're on **MSTest v4+**, use `Assert.ThrowsExactly<T>` instead (the v4 rename). You can also capture the exception to assert on its message:

```csharp
var ex = Assert.ThrowsExactly<ArgumentNullException>(
    () => service.CreateUser(null, "John"));
Assert.AreEqual("email", ex.ParamName);
```
